\details{
\code{assign_replication_by_seed()} evaluates seed feasibility for each
non-check treatment assigned to a single environment and partitions those
treatments into replication roles — replicated, unreplicated, or excluded —
according to the requested design mode and the available seed quantity per
treatment. The output is intended as direct input to \code{prep_famoptg()}, which
constructs the within-environment field layout from the resulting role
assignments.

Let \eqn{s_i} be the seed available for treatment \eqn{i}, \eqn{q} the seed
required per plot, \eqn{r} the requested replication count
(\code{desired_replications}), and \eqn{b} the minimum seed buffer
(\code{minimum_seed_buffer}). The feasibility conditions are:

\deqn{s_i \geq q + b \quad \text{(feasible for one unreplicated plot)}}
\deqn{s_i \geq r \times q + b \quad \text{(feasible for } r \text{ replicated plots)}}

A treatment that fails the first condition cannot be placed in any plot and
is excluded regardless of mode. A treatment that satisfies the first but not
the second condition can support one plot but not the target replication; its
fate under shortage depends on \code{replication_mode} and \code{shortage_action}.
\subsection{Replication modes}{

\strong{\code{"augmented"}}: All treatments are targeted for a single unreplicated
plot. Treatments satisfying \eqn{s_i \geq q + b} are assigned the role
\code{"unreplicated"}. Those that fail are assigned \code{"excluded"} if
\code{shortage_action} is \code{"exclude"} or \code{"downgrade"}, or trigger an error if
\code{shortage_action = "error"}.

\strong{\code{"p_rep"}}: A selection of treatments is designated for replication at
\code{desired_replications}; the remaining treatments are unreplicated.
Candidates for replication are drawn from \code{candidate_prep} (all treatments
if \code{NULL}) restricted to those satisfying the replicated feasibility
condition. Among those candidates, selection priority is determined by
\code{priority}: \code{"seed_available"} ranks by descending seed quantity,
\code{"input_order"} preserves the order of \code{treatments}, and \code{"random"} draws
uniformly. The number of replicated treatments is optionally capped by
\code{max_prep}. Treatments not selected for replication are evaluated for
single-plot feasibility and assigned \code{"unreplicated"} or \code{"excluded"}.

\strong{\code{"rcbd_type"}}: All treatments are targeted for \code{desired_replications}.
Treatments satisfying the replicated feasibility condition receive role
\code{"p_rep"} at the requested replication level. For treatments that fail,
behavior depends on \code{shortage_action}: \code{"error"} stops immediately;
\code{"exclude"} drops the treatment from the design; \code{"downgrade"} reduces the
treatment to a single unreplicated plot if the single-plot feasibility
condition is met, or excludes it otherwise.
}

\subsection{Role vocabulary}{

The function assigns each treatment one of four roles, stored in the
\code{Role} column of \code{seed_summary}:
\itemize{
\item \code{"p_rep"}: assigned \code{desired_replications} plots.
\item \code{"unreplicated"}: assigned exactly one plot.
\item \code{"excluded"}: assigned no plots; insufficient seed.
\item \code{"unused"}: treatment not matched in the seed data frame (internal flag).
}
}
